[normal]CST0003[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence from[bold] Peter Barron[bold](R[bold]etired Det. Chief Superintendent Metropolitan Police[bold] &amp; Head of TP Crime Recording[bold])[bold]1.    [bold]Introduction[bold]Although the Public Administration Select Committee is only consid
[normal]ering ‘crime statistics’, it is 
[normal]impossible to understand the true situation without also considering ‘incident data’. I
[normal]n many cases, calls 
[normal]from members of the public are initi
[normal]ally recorded as ‘incidents’ only
[normal] some 
[normal]of which are 
[normal]later recorded as crimes. It is this ‘cradle-to-grave’ process that provides opportunities to influence 
[normal]if/when incidents are
[normal] recorded as crimes – and of those that are recorded as such – the specific type of crime that is recorded.
